#Summary1=(human1) This dictionary entry for the word 'school' gives its pronunciation /skuːl/, etymologies for its senses a group/to form a group of fish (from Middle English scole, Proto-Germanic *skulō 'crowd') and elementary school/to educate (from Proto-Germanic *skōla, from Late Latin schola, Ancient Greek σχολεῖον), along with cognates and usage examples as both noun and verb.

#Summary2=(claude-3-5-sonnet-20241022) This dictionary entry for 'school' outlines its dual etymology from Middle English, first meaning "group/multitude" and second meaning "place of education," provides pronunciation (/skuːl/), and details various definitions including groups of fish, educational institutions, art movements, and schools of thought, along with related verb forms.

#Summary3=(gpt4o) This dictionary entry for the word 'school' presents its pronunciation /skuːl/, etymology tracing back to Proto-Indo-European *(s)kʷel- meaning "crowd" and Ancient Greek σχολή meaning "leisure", its definitions as a noun referring to both an educational institution and a group of fish, alternative forms like 'schole', and verb usage meaning to educate or train.

#Summary4=(Meta-Llama-3-8B-Instruct; postedited) The term "school" has multiple meanings, referring to a group of fish, an educational institution, a place of learning, or a method of teaching, with various etymologies and cognates across Germanic languages.

#Summary5=(Qwen2.5-3B-Instruct) This dictionary entry for the word 'school' provides its etymology surpassed in Middle English, cognates, pronunciations, definitions as a noun and verb, synonyms, and usage examples across various contexts including education, marine life, and art movements.
#Text=school
#Text=English
#Text=Pronunciation
#Text=enPR : sko͞ol , IPA ( key ) : / skuːl /
#Text=Audio ( Received Pronunciation )
#Text=Rhymes : -uːl
#Text=Etymology 1

#Text=From Middle English scole , schole ( “ group of persons , multitude , host , school of fish ” ) , from Middle Dutch scole ( “ multitude , troop of people , swarm of animals ” ) , from Old Dutch *scola , *skola ( “ troop , multitude ” ) , from Proto-Germanic *skulō ( “ crowd ” ) , from Proto-Indo-European *(s)kʷel- ( “ crowd , people ” ) .
#Text=Cognate with Middle Low German schōle ( “ multitude , troop ” ) , Old English scolu ( “ troop or band of people , host , multitude , school of fish ” ) . Doublet of shoal .
#Text=Alternative forms
#Text=skull ( obsolete )
#Text=Noun
#Text=school ( 1 ) of fish .
#Text=school ( plural schools )
#Text=( collective ) A group of fish or a group of marine mammals such as porpoises , dolphins , or whales .
#Text=The divers encountered a huge school of mackerel .
#Text=A multitude .
#Text=Synonyms
#Text=( fish ) : shoal
#Text=Verb
#Text=school ( third - person singular simple present schools , present participle schooling , simple past and past participle schooled )
#Text=( intransitive ) ( of fish ) To form into , or travel in a school .
#Text=Etymology 2
#Text=Elementary school

#Text=From Middle English scole , from Old English scōl ( “ place of education ” ) , from Proto-Germanic *skōla ( “ school ” ) , from Late Latin schola , scola ( “ learned discussion or dissertation , lecture , school ” ) , from Ancient Greek σχολεῖον ( skholeîon ) , from σχολή ( skholḗ , “ spare time , leisure ; conversations and the knowledge gained through them during free time ; the places where these conversations took place ” ) , from Proto-Indo-European *seǵʰ- ( “ to hold , have , possess ” ) .
#Text=Doublet of schola and shul .

#Text=Compare Old Frisian skūle , schūle ( “ school ” ) ( West Frisian skoalle , Saterland Frisian Skoule ) , Dutch school ( “ school ” ) , German Low German School ( “ school ” ) , Old High German scuola ( “ school ” ) , Old Norse skóli ( “ school ” ) .
#Text=Influenced in some senses by Middle English schole ( “ group of persons , host , company ” ) , from Middle Dutch scole ( “ multitude , troop , band ” ) .
#Text=See school 1 .
#Text=Related also to Old High German sigi ( German Sieg , “ victory ” ) , Old English siġe , sigor ( “ victory ” ) .
#Text=Alternative forms
#Text=schole ( obsolete )
#Text=Noun
#Text=school ( countable and uncountable , plural schools )
#Text=( US , Canada ) An institution dedicated to teaching and learning ; an educational institution .
#Text=Our children attend a public school in our neighborhood .
#Text=Harvard University is a famous American postsecondary school .
#Text=( Britain ) An educational institution providing primary and secondary education , prior to tertiary education ( college or university ) .
#Text=( UK ) At Eton College , a period or session of teaching .
#Text=Divinity , history and geography are studied for two schools per week .
#Text=Within a larger educational institution , an organizational unit , such as a department or institute , which is dedicated to a specific subject area .
#Text=We are enrolled in the same university , but I attend the School of Economics and my brother is in the School of Music .
#Text=An art movement , a community of artists .
#Text=The Barbizon school of painters were part of an art movement towards Realism in art , which arose in the context of the dominant Romantic Movement of the time .
#Text=( considered collectively ) The followers of a particular doctrine ; a particular way of thinking or particular doctrine ; a school of thought .
#Text=These economists belong to the monetarist school .
#Text=The time during which classes are attended or in session in an educational institution .
#Text=I 'll see you after school .
#Text=The room or hall in English universities where the examinations for degrees and honours are held .
#Text=The canons , precepts , or body of opinion or practice , sanctioned by the authority of a particular class or age .
#Text=He was a gentleman of the old school .
#Text=An establishment offering specialized instruction , as for driving , cooking , typing , coding , etc.
#Text=Synonyms
#Text=( institution dedicated to teaching and learning ) : academy , college , university
#Text=( organizational unity within an educational institution ) : college , department , faculty , institute
#Text=Hyponyms
#Text=See also Thesaurus : school
#Text=Coordinate terms
#Text=( institution providing primary and secondary education ) : nursery school , kindergarten , college , polytechnic , university
#Text=Verb
#Text=school ( third - person singular simple present schools , present participle schooling , simple past and past participle schooled )
#Text=( transitive ) To educate , teach , or train ( often , but not necessarily , in a school ) .
#Text=Many future prime ministers were schooled in Eton .
#Text=( transitive ) To defeat emphatically , to teach an opponent a harsh lesson .
#Text=( transitive ) To control , or compose , one 's expression .
#Text=She took care to school her expression , not giving away any of her feelings .
